<BaseLayout title="T1: Strategy Composition — CS8803 Reference" currentPath="/m1-strategy/t1-composition">

<section class="topic">
  <div class="topic-header">
    <div class="topic-num">T1</div>
    <h3>Strategy Composition</h3>
  </div>

  <LessonCard code="Mod 1 · Topic 1 · Lesson 1" title="Overview and Introduction" tags={[{label:"Course Overview"}]} searchData="overview introduction course perullo ciso ice nyse modules">
    <p>Professor Jerry Perullo brings 20 years as CISO at ICE (Intercontinental Exchange, parent of the NYSE), covering organizations from 40 to 10,000+ employees. The course covers four modules: <strong>Strategy → Cybersecurity Operations → Security Assurance → Governance</strong>.</p>
    <Callout variant="green">The instructor's background is critical infrastructure + Fortune 500 financial services — expect frameworks to be tested against high-stakes, regulated environments. Every recommendation is grounded in real operational experience, not theory.</Callout>
    <p>Learning outcomes span strategy writing, threat objective mapping, org design, CIRP, architecture strategy, risk triage, legislation, AppSec/red team methodology, internal governance, and board oversight — a complete enterprise security management toolkit.</p>
  </LessonCard>

  <LessonCard code="Mod 1 · Topic 1 · Lesson 2" title="Strategy History and Purpose" tags={[{label:"Framework",type:"fw"},{label:"Key Terms",type:"def"},{label:"Practical",type:"tip"}]} searchData="strategy purpose timeline roadmap board ratification business mission metrics">
    <div class="section-label">Why strategies historically failed</div>
    <p>Most early cybersecurity strategies were written solely to satisfy regulatory inquiries — resulting in generic documents that restated obvious truths ("we will protect CIA") without providing direction or business alignment. The lesson: a strategy written for compliance consumption rather than internal guidance is wasted effort.</p>

    <div class="section-label">What a good strategy must do</div>
    <ul class="bullet">
      <li>Be <strong>forward-looking</strong> (not describing current state — that's a policy, not a strategy)</li>
      <li>Tie cybersecurity objectives to the <strong>business mission</strong> — each section maps to programs in flight</li>
      <li>Set <strong>target-state metrics</strong> — define what you'll measure, not necessarily specific values today</li>
      <li>Define priority threat types and investment priorities — use the Threat Objective model</li>
      <li>Avoid vendor/technology specifics — overly prescriptive content becomes obsolete in 3 years</li>
      <li>"Red-team first" philosophy: if it can't be exploited or demonstrated, it didn't happen — don't claim it as a control</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="section-label">Structure and approval</div>
    <ul class="bullet">
      <li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 2–5 years; 3-year is most common; accompanied by a Gantt-style roadmap with owners and delivery dates</li>
      <li><strong>Each section contains:</strong> Description → Map to mission → Programs (get credit + tick compliance boxes) → Target-state metrics (most valuable but the section most likely to be misused)</li>
      <li><strong>Ratification:</strong> Must be formally approved by cross-functional senior management — ideally the board's risk or audit committee for public companies</li>
    </ul>

    <Callout variant="orange">Career tip: When a board approves your strategy, the CFO and GC are on record endorsing the priorities. That's invaluable when requesting resources later — you're not asking for budget, you're executing what was already approved.</Callout>
    <div class="lesson-refs">
      <span class="refs-label">See also</span>
      <a class="ref-link" href="https://nist.gov/cyberframework" target="_blank">NIST Cybersecurity Framework</a>
      <a class="ref-link" href="https://www.isaca.org/resources/cobit" target="_blank">COBIT Framework</a>
      <a class="ref-link" href="https://www.iso.org/standard/27001" target="_blank">ISO 27001</a>
    </div>
  </LessonCard>

  <LessonCard code="Mod 1 · Topic 1 · Lesson 3" title="NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)" tags={[{label:"Framework: NIST CSF",type:"fw"},{label:"5+1 Functions",type:"def"},{label:"CSF 2.0 (Feb 2024)",type:"new"}]} searchData="NIST CSF cybersecurity framework identify protect detect respond recover govern CSF 2.0">
    <p>The NIST CSF was created in 2014 for critical infrastructure but is now globally adopted across all sectors. Its original five functions provide a practical, intuitive structure for organizing a cybersecurity strategy — not an exhaustive checklist of all 100+ subcategories.</p>

    <div class="section-label">The Original Five Functions (semi-chronological)</div>
    <ul class="bullet">
      <li><strong>Identify (ID):</strong> Asset management, business environment, governance, risk assessment, risk management strategy, supply chain. <em>Tip: Use this section to identify your business concerns, threat objectives, and regulatory environment — not just a technical asset list.</em></li>
      <li><strong>Protect (PR):</strong> Access control, awareness/training, data security, information protection processes, maintenance, protective technology. Describe control classes, not vendor products.</li>
      <li><strong>Detect (DE):</strong> Anomalies/events, continuous monitoring, detection processes. Key tools: SIEM, EDR, behavioral analytics, deception technology, IDS/IPS.</li>
      <li><strong>Respond (RS):</strong> Response planning (CIRP), communications, analysis, mitigation, improvements. Include tabletop exercises and analyst training commitments.</li>
      <li><strong>Recover (RC):</strong> Recovery planning, improvements, communications. Mostly IT/Operations-owned; CISO contributes communications planning. <em>Tip: Step in if nobody else owns this — it's a fast way to earn cross-functional credibility.</em></li>
    </ul>

    <Callout variant="purple"><strong>CSF 2.0 — Released February 2024:</strong> NIST added a sixth function: <strong>Govern (GV)</strong>. It covers organizational context, risk management strategy, roles/responsibilities/authorities, policies and procedures, oversight, and supply chain risk management. Critically, it elevates cybersecurity supply chain risk from a subcategory to a full category. CSF 2.0 also formally expands scope beyond critical infrastructure to <em>all</em> organizations, and formalizes the "Profiles" concept for maturity tracking. When organizing a strategy today, use six sections — not five.</Callout>

    <Callout>Practical: Use the NIST CSF functions as section headers in your strategy. This communicates recognized structure to regulators, board members, and auditors, and makes third-party maturity assessments easier to map.</Callout>
